<p>What is the associativity of comparison operators in Python? It is straightforward for three comparisons, but for more than that, I'm not sure how it does it. They don't seem to be right- or left-associative.</p>  <p>For example:</p>  <pre><code>&gt;&gt;&gt; 7410 &gt;= 8690 &lt;= -4538 &lt; 9319 &gt; -7092         False     &gt;&gt;&gt; (((7410 &gt;= 8690) &lt;= -4538) &lt; 9319) &gt; -7092  True </code></pre>  <p>So, not left-associative.</p>  <pre><code>&gt;&gt;&gt; 81037572 &gt; -2025 &lt; -4722 &lt; 6493            False &gt;&gt;&gt; (81037572 &gt; (-2025 &lt; (-4722 &lt; 6493)))      True </code></pre>  <p>So it's not right-associative either.</p>  <p>I have seen some places that they are 'chained', but how does that work with four or more comparisons?</p>